me are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Meurig","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Meuric","meanings":["From Latin <i>Mauricius</i> via Old Welsh <i>Mouric</i>.  See  <b>Maurice</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Wales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Wales near Sheffield (South Yorkshire). The placename means ‘The Welshmen’ and denoted a settlement of Brittonic speakers living on the boundary between the Anglo-Saxon kingdoms of Northumbria and Mercia (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). See also   Wallis  .","habitational name from Wales, the country named from Old English <i>wēalas</i> ‘foreigners’ (especially those speaking Celtic or Romance languages). This meaning of the surname is quite rare."],"variants":[{"name":"Wailes","meanings":["English: variant of   Wales  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is a derivative of   William ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwaithfoed ap Meurig of Wales was born about 1100, in Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Meurig Fychan ap Cydifor, was 21 and his mother, Gwladys Verch Ynyr, was 21. He married Lleucu verch Gwernystan before 1124, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1105–1211":"1105–1211","–Female":"Surnud","1124–Female":"1124–Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1080–1136":"1080–1136","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1105":"1105","1136":"1136","before 1124":"enne 1124","1124":"1124","1211":"1211","ABT    1130":"umbes 1130","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1124":"umbes 1124","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1180":"1180","Welshpool, Montgomery, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Ceredigion, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1105–1211":"1105–1211","–Female":"Kuollut","1124–Female":"1124–Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1080–1136":"1080–1136","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1105":"1105","1136":"1136","before 1124":"ennen vuotta 1124","1124":"1124","1211":"1211","ABT    1130":"noin 1130","1100":"1100","1130":"1130","about 1124":"noin 1124","about 1100":"noin 1100","1180":"1180","Welshpool, Montgomery, Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wales":"Wales","Ceredigion, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,,Cardiganshire,